The good old days... 

Along with my old man and my mom, my grandparents made my childhood - and most formative years of my life - an everlasting memory of joy, happiness, and love.

I owe my granddad my first love for America, for the cowboy, for the West, for History.  All my childhood I watched Western Movies with him. He couldn't speak one word of English and to be honest, couldn't care less about America, but the man loved cowboys! 
He died in 2003. 
He taught me to be precise in my thoughts, my words, my actions.
The unbelievable - but true - story of his life during World War II will be one I will share one day in a screenplay.

My grandma - ma mamie chérie - taught me kindness, devotion to the ones you love, strenght, resilience, and blessed me with unconditional love. She also gave all these beautiful qualities to her daughter, my mom.

I call my grandma every single day of my life. She is my angel and it's the joy of my day to hear her voice and still she praises me for being a good grandson and thanks me for calling her! Talk about devotion!

All her life you could swear she was born an aristocrat or of royal blood, but she grew up as a poor country girl in a time when children were happy if they got an orange for Christmas. To this day, she has incredible class and impeccable posture. 

After 5 months in an hospital, she recently came back to her home, still smiling and laughing at 93yo, with the constant care of my mom who stays with her. Being an angel runs in the women in my family...

A close group of brothers have prayed with me these last 5 months when she was suffering, when she couldn't take it anymore, when our hearts were heavy... She knew it. They helped her so much. 
Her, my mom, and I, are thankful for them, and so grateful for His work.

Thank you my beautiful wife, Gigi, for setting the tone for our whole family. You are my everlasting Christmas miracle. You are behind everything good in our sons and myself.

Thank you my spiritual brother, Randy, for having strenghten my faith and my resolve since our paths crossed. I look forward to grow old next to you my dear friend and neighbor.

Thank you Pastor Shaun Groves, for having been such a solid hand and a calm voice.

Thank you Church of the City for what you do for the community here around Nashville.

Thank you Amy, Ava, Anna, Gabriel, Ashley, Shane, Katherine, Shawn, Julie, John, Kim, Matt, Lisa, Mark, Mary Ann, Dave, Jestine, Damon - and your children - McKenna, Matt. 
I love y'all! I will cherish your smiles, your words, the sweet memories of this day for the rest of my life here.

To my sons - @thomas.grazer and @patrick.grazer - you are such an important part of this day, as you are such a vital piece of who I am and how I wish to be remembered. When I count my blessings, I see your faces first in my mind.

God Bless you, my beautiful boys.

Franklin, Tennessee, USA.
February, 5th, 2023.

Today and every day, my everything, my everlasting Christmas miracle.

Is the American Dream alive or dead? It’s a question that begs asking but more importantly, how can we each, individually carve out our own piece of it if possible?

These are all questions my guest today, Chris Elise (@froyourmind), and I address. Chris was born in France and has since become an American citizen following his dreams as a young boy. Today, we talk about channeling anger for productive outcomes, how to develop a personal renewal of faith, why you need to be cautious of betraying yourself, not getting yourself stuck in a bubble, investing in brotherhood, and pursuing your version of the American Dream.

Check the link in our bio for the full conversation…

One week ago I was shooting  @theamerican.tr for @tetonridge in Arlington, Texas.

Wonderful experience, working for the great people at @tetonridge being part of a dream team of action photographers - the talented and coolest @clickthompson the Rodeo & Western king @pintargraphy and the awesome Adventure photographer @michaelclarkphoto (Risk should be his middle name!)

Check the art they display, it's truly breathtaking!

Grateful for the opportunity to always learn more, to work on sports and a culture I love, admire and respect.

Thankful for @mandi_williams_ her team and the @pbr organization who welcomed me with open arms 5 years ago when I covered my first Western Sport event in Sioux Falls, SD. On the first day, @flintrasmussen invited me on the dirt for a skit about my 'fro, with his talented humor and kindness. To this day it's a good memory Flint. Thank you!
Y'all at @pbr from @pbrceo to @mitchdevine @mattlwest and so many to mention put me in the saddle and made this opportunity possible along the years.

A special thank you to my good friend @chrisdouglasphoto 
Your appreciation of my work means the world to me Chris!

Can't wait for the next time! 
🙏🏽
